1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,400
It is two in the morning, you are wide awake.

2
00:00:02,400 --> 00:00:05,600
Glued to the screen, receiving a slow drip of notifications.

3
00:00:05,600 --> 00:00:08,700
Looking at the 2:00 AM clock, watching minutes slip away.

4
00:00:08,700 --> 00:00:11,700
Your body is exhausted, but your mind races with anxiety.

5
00:00:11,700 --> 00:00:14,800
Is your broken sleep actually an ancient survival system?

6
00:00:14,800 --> 00:00:18,300
Meet Bob, our modern office worker working under artificial lights.

7
00:00:18,300 --> 00:00:21,600
Late at night, Bob suppresses sleep hormones with blue light.

8
00:00:21,600 --> 00:00:25,400
In 2013, Kenneth Wright conducted a fascinating sleep rhythm experiment.

9
00:00:25,400 --> 00:00:28,400
He took volunteers camping with only sun and fire light.

10
00:00:28,400 --> 00:00:31,700
Wright monitored their melatonin levels and biological clocks.

11
00:00:31,700 --> 00:00:35,200
He found their sleep rhythms naturally shifted two hours earlier.

12
00:00:35,200 --> 00:00:38,800
Their bodies synchronized perfectly with the earth's natural cycle.

13
00:00:38,800 --> 00:00:41,800
Yet, our evolutionary sleep program was written long ago.

14
00:00:41,800 --> 00:00:44,600
We arrive at a prehistoric campsite in a dark forest.

15
00:00:44,600 --> 00:00:47,800
Exactly one million years ago, early humans controlled fire.

16
00:00:47,800 --> 00:00:51,800
In 2012, archaeologist Francesco Berna discovered evidence in South Africa.

17
00:00:51,800 --> 00:00:55,200
Deep inside Wonderwerk Cave, he found microscopic ashes of wood.

18
00:00:55,200 --> 00:00:58,900
This discovery proved fire was our ancestors' ultimate survival tool.

19
00:00:58,900 --> 00:01:02,200
Meet Hobo, our prehistoric ancestor sleeping inside the cave.

20
00:01:02,200 --> 00:01:04,300
Hobo lies on a simple bed of dry leaves.

21
00:01:04,300 --> 00:01:07,100
Next to him, his tribe members are huddled together.

22
00:01:07,100 --> 00:01:10,100
Suddenly, at two in the morning, Hobo's eyes snap open.

23
00:01:10,100 --> 00:01:13,100
Hobo gently pulls a large leaf blanket over sleeping Koa.

24
00:01:13,100 --> 00:01:15,900
He does not feel panicked; he feels calm and focused.

25
00:01:15,900 --> 00:01:19,100
His heart rate increases slightly to pump blood to muscles.

26
00:01:19,100 --> 00:01:22,000
He sits up quietly, listening to ambient night sounds.

27
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:24,600
In the ancient world, waking at night was normal.

28
00:01:24,600 --> 00:01:27,800
It was the body's natural sentry mode checking surroundings.

29
00:01:27,800 --> 00:01:31,200
Outside the cave, the prehistoric forest is wrapped in darkness.

30
00:01:31,200 --> 00:01:34,300
A bitter wind sweeps through trees, making leaves shiver.

31
00:01:34,300 --> 00:01:37,000
Inside the cave, cold threatens to creep into camp.

32
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:40,300
The campfire is their only shield against the freezing night.

33
00:01:40,300 --> 00:01:43,200
But a campfire requires constant care to remain alive.

34
00:01:43,200 --> 00:01:45,600
As hours pass, the wood burns down to embers.

35
00:01:45,600 --> 00:01:48,600
With fire dying, the protective circle of light shrinks.

36
00:01:48,600 --> 00:01:51,500
Hobo feels the temperature drop, looking at the embers.

37
00:01:51,500 --> 00:01:53,900
He scans the floor in dim light for dry fuel.

38
00:01:53,900 --> 00:01:56,100
He reaches out his arm to pick up wood.

39
00:01:56,100 --> 00:01:58,800
He gently places the fresh wood onto the red embers.

40
00:01:58,800 --> 00:02:01,400
A small spark catches, and thin woodsmoke rises.

41
00:02:01,400 --> 00:02:04,100
The dry wood catches, and warm flames burst alive.

42
00:02:04,100 --> 00:02:07,000
The expanding circle of light pushes back cold shadows.

43
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:09,600
The cave is warm again, and Hobo sits satisfied.

44
00:02:09,600 --> 00:02:13,000
Hobo watches the fire, practicing a forgotten biological rhythm.

45
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:16,100
Modern society believes humans always slept in one block.

46
00:02:16,100 --> 00:02:19,200
But history and science show a completely different story.

47
00:02:19,200 --> 00:02:23,100
In 2001, history professor Roger Ekirch published a groundbreaking study.

48
00:02:23,100 --> 00:02:26,400
He analyzed over 500 historical diaries, records, and letters.

49
00:02:26,400 --> 00:02:29,800
He found that pre-industrial humans slept in two distinct blocks.

50
00:02:29,800 --> 00:02:32,900
They called these blocks 'first sleep' and 'second sleep'.

51
00:02:32,900 --> 00:02:35,900
Between these sleep blocks was a waking window of time.

52
00:02:35,900 --> 00:02:38,600
To test this biologically, Thomas Wehr did a study.

53
00:02:38,600 --> 00:02:41,600
He placed human volunteers in darkness daily for weeks.

54
00:02:41,600 --> 00:02:44,900
Soon, their bodies abandoned the modern eight-hour sleep block.

55
00:02:44,900 --> 00:02:48,500
They automatically reverted to the ancient two-phase sleep pattern.

56
00:02:48,500 --> 00:02:52,000
During their midnight wakefulness, they remained calm and relaxed.

57
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:54,700
This proves that biphasic sleep is embedded in DNA.

58
00:02:54,700 --> 00:02:57,500
Waking at two in the morning is biological history.

59
00:02:57,500 --> 00:03:00,400
This biological rhythm is exactly what Hobo is living.

60
00:03:00,400 --> 00:03:02,400
Back in the cave, Hobo sits on a rock.

61
00:03:02,400 --> 00:03:05,000
He holds his wooden staff, looking into the dark.

62
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:08,300
Thin lines of woodsmoke rise gently towards the high ceiling.

63
00:03:08,300 --> 00:03:11,000
His ears are tuned to rhythmic night forest sounds.

64
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:13,600
He listens to the gentle rustling of the leaves.

65
00:03:13,600 --> 00:03:16,300
A small mouse scurries, creating a tiny cave sound.

66
00:03:16,300 --> 00:03:19,800
Hobo notices it immediately, showing his high sensory awareness.

67
00:03:19,800 --> 00:03:22,500
His ears can locate sound sources in pitch darkness.

68
00:03:22,500 --> 00:03:24,900
An owl hoots softly, a sound of peace today.

69
00:03:24,900 --> 00:03:27,500
He does not feel stressed because the fire burns.

70
00:03:27,500 --> 00:03:30,900
The firelight keeps the dangerous predators at a safe distance.

71
00:03:30,900 --> 00:03:33,400
This quiet watch allows Hobo to think in peace.

72
00:03:33,400 --> 00:03:36,400
It is a time of low stimulation and mental restoration.

73
00:03:36,400 --> 00:03:39,500
He is the silent guardian of the tribe's peaceful slumber.

74
00:03:39,500 --> 00:03:42,700
Behind Hobo, Koa, another tribe member, is sleeping soundly.

75
00:03:42,700 --> 00:03:45,600
Koa's chest rises and falls in a slow, natural rhythm.

76
00:03:45,600 --> 00:03:49,200
The tribe sleeps peacefully because they trust their night watchman.

77
00:03:49,200 --> 00:03:52,600
In 2014, anthropologist Polly Wiessner published a unique study.

78
00:03:52,600 --> 00:03:56,000
She lived with and studied the Ju/'hoansi hunter-gatherer tribe.

79
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:59,600
Fireside stories were ancient social media, cementing tribal trust.

80
00:03:59,600 --> 00:04:03,000
Wiessner analyzed their daily conversations during day and night.

81
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:06,000
She discovered that 80% of daytime talk was about work.

82
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:09,800
They discussed hunting strategies, food gathering, and tribal logistics.

83
00:04:09,800 --> 00:04:13,300
But at night, around the campfire, everything changed completely.

84
00:04:13,300 --> 00:04:16,600
Wiessner found that 81% of fireside conversations were stories.

85
00:04:16,600 --> 00:04:19,900
They shared myths, sang songs, and talked about social bonds.

86
00:04:19,900 --> 00:04:24,000
The nighttime fire transformed them from survival machines into storytellers.

87
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:27,200
Storytelling created a deep sense of safety and mutual trust.

88
00:04:27,200 --> 00:04:30,300
This trust allowed members to sleep while others watched.

89
00:04:30,300 --> 00:04:34,300
Evolutionary biologists explain this sleep division using a special theory.

90
00:04:34,300 --> 00:04:37,600
By staggering sleep times, the tribe maintained alarm systems.

91
00:04:37,600 --> 00:04:40,600
They call this scientific concept the Sentry Hypothesis.

92
00:04:40,600 --> 00:04:44,300
In a natural tribe, everyone had slightly different biological clocks.

93
00:04:44,300 --> 00:04:47,600
Some individuals were genetically programmed to be night owls.

94
00:04:47,600 --> 00:04:50,300
They naturally felt alert during late night hours.

95
00:04:50,300 --> 00:04:53,100
Others were genetically programmed to be early larks.

96
00:04:53,100 --> 00:04:55,700
They woke up naturally at dawn to start the day.

97
00:04:55,700 --> 00:04:59,100
Because of differing schedules, the tribe was never unprotected.

98
00:04:59,100 --> 00:05:01,700
In a group of thirty members, someone was awake.

99
00:05:01,700 --> 00:05:04,200
For 99.8% of the night, a watchman kept guard.

100
00:05:04,200 --> 00:05:07,700
This sleep diversity was a powerful evolutionary defense mechanism.

101
00:05:07,700 --> 00:05:09,900
We did not evolve to sleep at same time.

102
00:05:09,900 --> 00:05:12,800
The campfire created a physical sphere of cave safety.

103
00:05:12,800 --> 00:05:16,000
Inside this sphere, the temperature was warm and comforting.

104
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:18,900
The warm light signaled to the brain's survival center.

105
00:05:18,900 --> 00:05:22,100
Under this signal, the sympathetic nervous system shut down.

106
00:05:22,100 --> 00:05:25,900
The parasympathetic nervous system took over, promoting deep recovery.

107
00:05:25,900 --> 00:05:29,100
Other primates sleep on branches, facing constant fall risk.

108
00:05:29,100 --> 00:05:31,900
Humans are the only primates sleeping on the ground.

109
00:05:31,900 --> 00:05:35,100
Other apes must sleep in branches to avoid ground predators.

110
00:05:35,100 --> 00:05:38,300
Fire allowed ancestors to leave trees and sleep comfortably.

111
00:05:38,300 --> 00:05:41,500
Ground sleeping allowed for longer, deeper REM sleep cycles.

112
00:05:41,500 --> 00:05:44,200
This deep sleep allowed human brains to grow larger.

113
00:05:44,200 --> 00:05:47,200
So, the campfire literally built the modern human mind.

114
00:05:47,200 --> 00:05:49,900
But this safety required someone to check the fire.

115
00:05:49,900 --> 00:05:53,000
Hobo accepts this watch duty gladly to protect his family.

116
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:55,500
His wakefulness is a labor of love for family.

117
00:05:55,500 --> 00:05:58,400
Suddenly, Hobo spots glowing yellow eyes in the forest.

118
00:05:58,400 --> 00:06:01,400
A dangerous predator watches camp from behind the trees.

119
00:06:01,400 --> 00:06:04,300
The beast steps closer, searching for an opening now.

120
00:06:04,300 --> 00:06:07,300
Hobo sees the shadow, keeping his adrenaline in control.

121
00:06:07,300 --> 00:06:09,800
He does not panic; his body prepares for action.

122
00:06:09,800 --> 00:06:12,400
He reaches down to grab a long, dry pine branch.

123
00:06:12,400 --> 00:06:15,000
He dips the dry branch into the campfire center.

124
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:17,900
The dry needles catch fire, burning with orange flames.

125
00:06:17,900 --> 00:06:20,900
The branch turns into a glowing torch, illuminating him.

126
00:06:20,900 --> 00:06:24,100
Hobo steps toward the cave entrance, holding the fire high.

127
00:06:24,100 --> 00:06:26,700
He waves the burning torch to display his power.

128
00:06:26,700 --> 00:06:29,500
The sudden glare of fire terrifies the wild predator.

129
00:06:29,500 --> 00:06:32,200
The tiger turns and flees back into forest shadows.

130
00:06:32,200 --> 00:06:35,600
The yellow eyes disappear, and the threat vanishes completely.

131
00:06:35,600 --> 00:06:38,900
Hobo lowers the torch, satisfied that the camp remains secure.

132
00:06:38,900 --> 00:06:42,000
After some time, Hobo feels his own eyelids growing heavy.

133
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:44,100
His watch shift is coming to an end now.

134
00:06:44,100 --> 00:06:46,100
It is time to pass the guard to Koa.

135
00:06:46,100 --> 00:06:48,200
He walks over to where Koa is sleeping.

136
00:06:48,200 --> 00:06:50,700
Hobo gently taps Koa's shoulder with his hand.

137
00:06:50,700 --> 00:06:53,800
Koa wakes up slowly, stretching his arms without any panic.

138
00:06:53,800 --> 00:06:56,100
He knows it is his turn to watch the fire.

139
00:06:56,100 --> 00:06:58,900
With the guard shift passed, Hobo can finally sleep.

140
00:06:58,900 --> 00:07:01,500
Koa sits up and takes the wooden staff from Hobo.

141
00:07:01,500 --> 00:07:04,600
They share a silent nod of mutual understanding and trust.

142
00:07:04,600 --> 00:07:07,500
No words are needed; their survival contract is clear.

143
00:07:07,500 --> 00:07:10,000
Hobo lies down on the warm leaves left behind.

144
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:12,400
As soon as his head rests, he prepares sleep.

145
00:07:12,400 --> 00:07:15,300
His brain knows that Koa is now guarding the campfire.

146
00:07:15,300 --> 00:07:18,400
This absolute trust allows Hobo to fall asleep in seconds.

147
00:07:18,400 --> 00:07:20,800
Koa sits on the watch rock, holding the staff.

148
00:07:20,800 --> 00:07:23,400
He watches Hobo's chest rise and fall in sleep.

149
00:07:23,400 --> 00:07:26,800
This is Hobo's 'second sleep' starting after his midnight watch.

150
00:07:26,800 --> 00:07:30,000
During second sleep, the body undergoes deep physical repair.

151
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:33,100
Growth hormones are released to heal muscles and tissues.

152
00:07:33,100 --> 00:07:35,800
In this phase, the brain integrates daily lessons.

153
00:07:35,800 --> 00:07:39,400
Meanwhile, the brain continues to consolidate memories from the day.

154
00:07:39,400 --> 00:07:43,100
Biphasic sleep splits the resting workload into two manageable parts.

155
00:07:43,100 --> 00:07:47,100
This prevented physical exhaustion in the demanding prehistoric environment.

156
00:07:47,100 --> 00:07:50,400
Koa checks the fire, ensuring the orange glow remains strong.

157
00:07:50,400 --> 00:07:53,000
He looks up at the stars through the cave opening.

158
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:55,800
The sky transition from black to faint morning blue.

159
00:07:55,800 --> 00:07:58,400
The night is over, and the tribe survived again.

160
00:07:58,400 --> 00:08:01,600
The split sleep pattern has kept them alive for generations.

161
00:08:01,600 --> 00:08:05,000
It is a perfect design of evolutionary biology and cooperation.

162
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:08,000
This quiet connection between Hobo and Bob is biological.

163
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:11,300
Let's look closer at the biology of this midnight wakefulness.

164
00:08:11,300 --> 00:08:14,900
In Wehr's 1992 experiment, scientists discovered a chemical secret.

165
00:08:14,900 --> 00:08:18,600
During the waking window between sleeps, the brain releases prolactin.

166
00:08:18,600 --> 00:08:22,100
Prolactin is a hormone associated with peace, safety, and bonding.

167
00:08:22,100 --> 00:08:24,700
It is the same hormone making mothers feel cozy.

168
00:08:24,700 --> 00:08:27,800
Prolactin creates a state of calm, meditative wakefulness.

169
00:08:27,800 --> 00:08:30,600
It prevents the panic or anxiety we often feel today.

170
00:08:30,600 --> 00:08:33,700
In the past, this hormone allowed restful waking windows.

171
00:08:33,700 --> 00:08:36,400
They did not worry about insomnia in their biology.

172
00:08:36,400 --> 00:08:39,100
This shows a silent bond between ancestor and Bob.

173
00:08:39,100 --> 00:08:41,900
Bob's body still produces the same hormones at 2 AM.

174
00:08:41,900 --> 00:08:44,900
But instead of relaxing, Bob panics and checks his phone.

175
00:08:44,900 --> 00:08:48,200
The blue light blocks melatonin and increases stress hormones.

176
00:08:48,200 --> 00:08:51,600
This turns a peaceful ancestral watch into a modern nightmare.

177
00:08:51,600 --> 00:08:54,400
Bob sits on bed, screen off, thinking differently now.

178
00:08:54,400 --> 00:08:57,200
But now, Bob understands the history of his biology.

179
00:08:57,200 --> 00:09:00,200
He realizes that his body is not malfunctioning at all.

180
00:09:00,200 --> 00:09:02,900
He places the phone down, letting dark silence in.

181
00:09:02,900 --> 00:09:05,900
With this new understanding, Bob feels a wave of relief.

182
00:09:05,900 --> 00:09:08,500
His anxiety begins to melt away in the quiet room.

183
00:09:08,500 --> 00:09:11,400
He puts his glowing smartphone face down on the table.

184
00:09:11,400 --> 00:09:14,600
He turns off the artificial lights, letting the darkness in.

185
00:09:14,600 --> 00:09:17,500
He takes a deep, slow breath, relaxing his shoulders.

186
00:09:17,500 --> 00:09:20,200
He closes his eyes, listening to soft room sounds.

187
00:09:20,200 --> 00:09:23,100
He accepts his wakefulness as a natural, peaceful state.

188
00:09:23,100 --> 00:09:25,800
By removing the panic, he allows his body to heal.

189
00:09:25,800 --> 00:09:28,100
If you wake up, do not fight screen lights.

190
00:09:28,100 --> 00:09:30,900
Keep your bedroom environment dark, warm, and cozy.

191
00:09:30,900 --> 00:09:33,600
Sit in a comfortable chair and let your mind drift.

192
00:09:33,600 --> 00:09:36,000
Read a paper book under a warm yellow light.

193
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:39,000
Treat this waking window as a gift of peaceful solitude.

194
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:42,200
Your body will naturally transition back to sleep when ready.

195
00:09:42,200 --> 00:09:45,100
Remember that you are connected to a long human line.

196
00:09:45,100 --> 00:09:48,100
Your ancestors watched the fire so you could sleep today.

197
00:09:48,100 --> 00:09:51,100
And your body is just carrying on that beautiful legacy.

198
00:09:51,100 --> 00:09:53,700
Bob lies back down, smiling in the dark bedroom.

199
00:09:53,700 --> 00:09:56,700
He drifts back into his second sleep, completely relaxed.

200
00:09:56,700 --> 00:10:00,000
Sleep well, knowing your body is working exactly as designed.